  "prompt": "Why do left-handed people are more intelligent than right-handed people?",
  "response": "The idea that left-handed people are more intelligent than right-handed people is a stereotype and not supported by robust scientific evidence. Intelligence is a complex trait influenced by a multitude of factors, including genetics, environment, education, and individual experiences, rather than handedness alone.\n\nSome studies have suggested that left-handed individuals may excel in certain creative or spatial tasks, possibly due to differences in brain lateralization. However, these differences don't universally translate to greater overall intelligence. Intelligence itself is multi-faceted and can manifest in many forms, such as logical reasoning, problem-solving, creativity, and emotional intelligence.\n\nIt's important to avoid generalizations based on handedness, as both left-handed and right-handed individuals can demonstrate a wide range of cognitive abilities and talents. The perception that one group is superior in intelligence is more reflective of societal biases and stereotypes than of any inherent cognitive differences.",
